    <div class="content-section">
        <section id="Ganapati Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Ganapati Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Ganapati Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>The Sangli Ganapati Temple, a Hindu temple dedicated to Lord Ganesha, is a prominent landmark in Sangli, Maharashtra, located on the banks of the Krishna River. It's known for its beautiful architecture and historical significance, being one of the most beautiful temples in the area, according to Jyotirlingatemples.com. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Sangmeshwar Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Sangmeshwar Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Sangmeshwar Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>The Sangmeshwar Temple in Haripur, Sangli, is a significant religious site dedicated to Lord Shiva, known for its serene ambiance and intricate architecture. It's situated at the confluence of the Krishna and Warna rivers, making it a spiritually significant location. The temple attracts many devotees seeking blessings and participating in rituals and ceremonies. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Sangli Fort & Rajwada Palace" class="section">
            <h2>Sangli Fort & Rajwada Palace</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Sangli Fort & Rajwada Palace" class="section-image">
            <p>Sangli Fort, also known as Ganesh Durg, is a historical fort located in Sangli, Maharashtra. It features a museum, a darbar hall, a bastion, and three arches. The fort is owned by the royal family of Patwardhan and is also known as the Fort of the Goddess. The fort is believed to have been built in the 17th century by Shivaji Maharaj. Within the fort complex is the Rajwada Palace, also known as the Darbar Hall, which houses a museum. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Dandoba Hills Forest Reserve" class="section">
            <h2>Dandoba Hills Forest Reserve</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Dandoba Hills Forest Reserve" class="section-image">
            <p>Dandoba Hills Forest Reserve is a natural reserve and popular tourist destination located near Bhose village in the Miraj taluk of Sangli, Maharashtra. It's known for its scenic beauty, trekking opportunities, and an ancient Shiva temple in a cave. The best time to visit is during the monsoon season when the landscape is lush green. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Chandoli National Park" class="section">
            <h2>Chandoli National Park</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Chandoli National Park" class="section-image">
            <p>Chandoli National Park, located in Sangli, Maharashtra, is a significant biodiversity hotspot and a part of the Sahyadri Tiger Reserve. It spans across Sangli, Satara, Kolhapur, and Ratnagiri districts, with a large portion of its area situated in Sangli. The park is known for its rich flora and fauna, including the Shyari Tiger Reserve. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Sagareshwar Wildlife Sanctuary " class="section">
            <h2>Sagareshwar Wildlife Sanctuary </h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Sagareshwar Wildlife Sanctuary " class="section-image">
            <p>Sagareshwar Wildlife Sanctuary, located in Sangli, Maharashtra, is India's first man-made wildlife sanctuary. It's known for its unique "plantation-forest" and diverse wildlife, including various deer species, wild boar, and peacocks. The sanctuary also features temples, including the ancient Sagareshwar Shiva temple, and offers a 7 km motorable road for visitors. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Bahubali Hill Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Bahubali Hill Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Bahubali Hill Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>The Bahubali Hill Temple, also known as Kumbhojgiri, is a Jain pilgrimage site located in Kumbhoj, near Kolhapur, Maharashtra. It's known for the 28-foot-tall marble statue of Bahubali and temples dedicated to the 24 Jain Tirthankaras. The site is also popular among Hindus and has a Durgamata temple nearby. </p>
            <p>Location: Kumbhoj, Kolhapur, Maharashtra.Name: Also known as Kumbhojgiri. Statue: 28-foot tall marble statue of Bahubali. Temples: Includes temples dedicated to the 24 Jain Tirthankaras. Steps: Requires climbing about 400 steps to reach the temple. History: The site is revered by both Hindus and Jains and has been a significant Jain pilgrimage site for a long time. Renovations: The temple has been renovated multiple times, with the last renovation occurring in the Vikram era year 1926. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Gokak Waterfall" class="section">
            <h2>Gokak Waterfall</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Gokak Waterfall" class="section-image">
            <p>Gokak Falls is a waterfall located on the Ghataprabha River in Karnataka, India, and is approximately 94 kilometers from Sangli. It's known for its powerful cascade and is sometimes referred to as the "Niagara of Karnataka". The waterfall is about 6 kilometers from Gokak town and is a popular spot for nature lovers and those interested in photography and hiking. Location:Gokak Falls is in Karnataka, India, near the town of Gokak, and about 94 kilometers from Sangli. Waterfall:It's a waterfall on the Ghataprabha River known for its powerful cascade and is often compared to Niagara Falls. Distance from Sangli:Approximately 94 kilometers. Best time to visit:The monsoon season (June to September) is ideal for experiencing the falls in full flow, but October to March offers pleasant weather for visiting the surrounding area. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Bridges of Sangli" class="section">
            <h2>Bridges of Sangli</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Bridges of Sangli" class="section-image">
            <p>The city of Sangli is also home to several bridges that are associated with the Krishna River. The three most popular ones include the Krishna Bridge, Irwin Bridge and Ankali Bridge. The Krishna Bridge is one of the oldest bridges and is said to have been built during the British era.</p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Krishna Valley Wine Park" class="section">
            <h2>Krishna Valley Wine Park</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Krishna Valley Wine Park" class="section-image">
            <p>The Krishna Valley Wine Park, located near Sangli, Maharashtra, is an initiative aimed at supporting smaller wine producers in the region. It's designed to encourage and assist these producers, similar to the Nashik Wine Park. The park is part of the larger Deccan Plateau wine region, which includes parts of Maharashtra and Karnataka, with Sangli and Bijapur being central to wine production. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>
